... but, to answer your question, the data you feed into the network won’t effect it, unless the others choose to never give your up, sorry, train on your, data.

The data is only used to train your own part of the collective system, you serve that trained component to other so they can use it. If they find value in Ricks obstinate love lyrics they will weight you in the incentive mechanism — giving you more value and more inflation
Having the minted token gives you the ability to penetrate the network with your stellar lyrics and understand their philosophically potent meaning, for what ever purpose you choose
In other words, Tao would gate access to the network’s understanding of the lyrics, perhaps the truest Rick roll ever experienced

How do the other nodes "find value" in my rickrolled model? Is it whatever reduces the error of the distributed model? If that's the case, what if we have many nodes training on similar data? Like many nodes running on rick rolls?

Each node has a subjective loss function, the things it cares about I.e summarizing texts or finding sentiment in text, or most likely, trying to build a unsupervised understanding of text using our genesis dataset.
As they train to understand their specific problem they use gradient descent (they learn) to filter the outputs of others in the network, specifically they weight them together using a conditional computation layer, like PKM or SGMOE. Those weights become the mechanism weights which determine inflation.
So, because those weights reflect value to the subjective losses, they also reflect value to the meta loss, or the sum of the loss as described in the paper.

The goal is actually to have many models train on similar data, this way the meta loss has some reasonable foundation. In all likelihood this will be a general unsupervised loss function, like that used to train GPT, an objective which produces a learned representation of inputs, from masses of unlabeled corpora pulled from books and the internet, which is useful to all problems — to step into the realm of sci fi a little, it’s here we want to find AGI, the big kahoona of general intelligence.
It's like asking a bunch of people how many jelly beans are in a jar. The average of the people's answers are closer to the true value in the jar.
Yes, but even further, the problems is so multi modal that you want to separate the people into sub groups and sub groups of subgroups, asking only the jelly bean experts what they think.

By learning which experts are useful to which inputs the network can partition the problem — if you want to add Rick Ashley to the mix, the others will find you, if only for the occasional inspiration
What about using the model as trained by the network? Let's say, for example, I wanted to generate words from an input prompt. How would I go about doing that?

The outputs of the other models are representations, these are tensors, arrays of numbers of shape [batch size, sequence len, network dim]
Sequence length is the length of your sentence, batch size is the number of sentences and meteor dim is the dimensionality of each representation
Representations are semantic, they are points in high dimensional space where the location of other points in reference to them coincide with meaning
For example the representation of the word king minus the representation of the word queen is the representation of the word male
Regardless, the outputs reflect the meaning of a sentence that your model can easily decode

One thing it can easily decode meaning into would be another sentence, like for instance, the response to the question posed. The meaning of the answer is encoded in the meaning of the question. Or the translation is encoded in the meaning of the original text
For your specific example, if you want to generate words from an input prompt you would want to decode the meaning of the prompt into the likely next sentence
You then feed the decoded sentence into the same process and you have GPT rambling opinions on climate change like a good redditor
Finally, and this is key, you want to distill what your model learns into an offline model, but that’s a different topic

Very cool project, has anyone attempted a brief explainlikeImfive for it? Asking for a friend 8-)

We don't have one but let me give it a shot:

Right now if you train an AI model to learn the english language, you can only train it in a siloed, lab-condition environment. This is why companies like google and Facebook have massive amounts of compute to train their models (it cost openai $12.4M USD just for the compute power to train their gpt 3 model, which is state of the art right now)

Bittensor takes this paradigm and throws it out the window. We instead break these models open and let computers run smaller versions of them, and each "tiny" model talks to the other models and tells them what it learned. It gets rewarded (with tao, our currency) if it learned something useful to the other models and shares it with them.

This way, we can achieve the same amount of compute as these massive companies but on a global scale, and machine intelligence becomes a commodity shared by all, instead of a select few engineers from big companies.

#!/usr/bin/env bash

count=0

_stopnow() {
    count="$(($count+1))"
    test -f stopnow && \
      echo "Stopping after $count iterations!" && \
      rm stopnow && exit 0 || return 0
}

control_c()
# run if user hits control-c
{
  echo "Managed to do $count iterations"
  exit $?
}

#trap keyboard interrupt (control-c)
trap control_c SIGINT

echo "To stop this forever loop created a file called stopnow."
echo "E.g: touch stopnow"
echo ""
echo "Now going to run '$@' forever"
echo ""
while true
do
    _stopnow

    eval $@

    # Do this in case you accidentally pass an argument
    # that finishes too quickly.
    sleep 1

done

Quick question: Why did you guys choose PyTorch over TensorFlow? (I hope that's not a stupid question)

No actually it's a great question @mootguy. ! 

The main reason is because we found PyTorch's code to be more readable and easier to work with developmentally. Bittensor started as a Tensorflow experiment, but Tensorflow's 2.0 release created a new learning curve for us when we started rewriting the code to be more scalable, and we found it very clunky. So we decided since we're starting from scratch, might as well learn PyTorch as it's a bit more developer friendly.
Additionally, we found GPU support on pytorch to be much more straightforward

Excited for the Bittensor upgrade. Will it still be friendly to low-mem 4GB CPU miners?
Taco! Yes it will be friendly to low-mem! We are even squeezing in a blockchain client too!
Relieved! Wait, so it didn't have a blockchain client in miner nodes before? Is this something different than what it had before ito posting block updates to substrate servers?

Yeah, in the past there wasn't a blockchain client, the nodes were connecting to external entrypoint nodes until we figured out a way to run the blockchain client with the miner at the same time.. the problem was that the chain was huge, so it wasn't practical to have miners run it
Ok, so with the upgrade will entrypoint nodes still be required, and will verifier nodes be required still? What will be the diff between blockchain client and substrate server?
So with the upgrades, the entrypoints shouldn't be needed so much anymore.
the bittensor client will run a smaller version of the blockchain (up to N blocks), so you don't need to synchronize the entire chain if you run it

so this would help us decentralize a lot faster, and at the same time we won't have a single point of entry anymore. If you remember when lots of folks joined the earlier network we experienced downtimes because the nodes couldn't keep up
this would eliminate that
Ok dope, but full clients will still be needed i suppose. Is the bittensor client then a modified (lightweight) substrate server?
yeah, that's essentially the idea
you can still run the full node if you want, but this is just to make it easier to run on more computers
as opposed to needing big rigs to run the full chain
Ok. And pretty please, make it so that miner startup time isn't affected too much, because I assume it'll be bogged down with blockchain syncing required at startup.
hahah that's exactly our next ticket item
they should ideally be decoupled
Very nice, this is a great development, wow, so it's really becoming proper decentralized now.
exactly yeah, we want the August launch to be a properly finalized version of the system. We're moving out of the beta stage
You know what this means, no more developer-instigated hard forks! 😋
Yep! that was our first and last one!
we're actively hiring more devs as well, so updates will be coming much faster
Great work, super.

PS. In smaller networks where the network is still heavily dependent on further dev work, the developers effectively can still instigate hardforks because miners are dependent on their continued support.
Correct, but we're hoping to get past that stage soon.
the sooner we hit critical mass, the better
Yes in theory, if big players can fund alternate chains then the option is there to really let the stakes decide.
So this is a comfort that this has these nice properties of a proper decentralized bc
yeah, good pooint
my point was that hard forks in the future are more for benefit, as opposed to fixing things
ok, yes, the criteria for hardforking needs to be exceptional. I believe bitcoin still has some of Satoshi's original bugs, which would indeed require hardfork to fix, but they keep the bugs instead.

“Finally, Peter Thiel has made the characteristically sweeping observation that AI is in some sense a left wing idea -- centralized machines making top-down decisions -- but crypto is a right wing idea -- many distributed agents, humans and bots, making bottom-up decisions. I think there’s something to that. Historically the tech industry has been dominated by left wing politics, just like any creative field, which is why you see today’s big tech companies so intertwined with the Democratic Party. Crypto potentially represents the creation of a whole new category of technology, quite literally right wing tech that is far more aggressively decentralized and far more comfortable with entrepreneurialism and free voluntary exchange. If you believe, as I do, that the world needs far more technology, this is a very powerful idea, a step function increase in what the technology world can do.”
@Taco ']

Love it when guys like Thiel talk about AI and crypto. Although, I'm more optimistic about what AI can do for the world once it widely embeds in the fabric of society. AI will deliver more surprises than crypto, because crypto prioritises self-regulation and orderliness whereas AI is relatively unconstrained. At any speed, the intersection of the two is super interesting, and once the Thiels of the world see what projects like bittensor are doing they'll be sure to look twice.

I'm very interested in whats going to happen when AI -- which is pretty unconstrained, disordered -- and crypto -- which is pretty ordered, constrained-- merge together. Kind of like the whole unstoppable force meeting an immovable object thing.
like the intersection of order and chaos...
ying yang
or tao

To add. I think the peter thiels of the world might be less interested in the reason we're doing this, but more interested in the implications. When bittensor takes off they'll inevitably come, but perhaps not for the right reasons.

It's an interesting point. Crypto currencies enable the creation of "hard" structure in digital space, while machine learning is primarily built off "soft" adaptive structure. The combination of the two is a bit like the combination of polar opposite elements.
